.update_enemy_slot
    JSR enemy_type_dispatch  \ Per-frame action for one enemy slot (X = slot index). Two steps: (1) call enemy_type_dispatch for the per-type immediate action; if the dispatch path bumped enemy_type past &14 (the death-anim range), jump to enemy_death_step. (2) Otherwise gate frame-advance on zp_7F == 4 (the animation phase tick — zp_7F cycles 3/4 across frames, so anim only advances 50% of the time) and fall into enemy_anim_advance.
    LDA enemy_type,X
    CMP #&14
    BCC L2260
    JMP enemy_death_step
.L2260
    LDA zp_7F
    CMP #&04
    BEQ enemy_anim_advance
    RTS

.enemy_anim_advance
    \ Animation-frame state machine for one enemy slot — keyed on enemy_type[X]:
    \ type < &04 → anim_loop_1_to_3 (small-enemy 3-frame loop: 1→2→3→1, with type 4 hit briefly to spawn a bullet then immediately wrapped back to 1)
    \ type &08 or &09 → anim_toggle_8_9 (EOR #1 — flame-firing enemy alternates between pre-fire pose &08 and post-fire idle &09)
    \ type &0F → anim_set_type_10 (2-frame loop with &10)
    \ type &10 → anim_set_type_F (2-frame loop with &0F)
    \ &04..&07, &0A..&0E, &11..&13 → enemy_anim_done (no animation — these are either action types that mutate to their own next state on dispatch, or static decor)
    \ type ≥ &14 → enemy_death_step (the explosion-animation tail).
    LDA enemy_type,X
    CMP #&04
    BCC anim_loop_1_to_3
    CMP #&08
    BEQ anim_toggle_8_9
    CMP #&09
    BEQ anim_toggle_8_9
    CMP #&0F
    BEQ anim_set_type_10
    CMP #&10
    BEQ anim_set_type_F
    CMP #&14
    BCC enemy_anim_done
    JMP enemy_death_step

.anim_loop_1_to_3
    INC enemy_type,X  \ Small-enemy 3-frame animation loop (types 1, 2, 3). INC type; on hitting type 4 (which is the 'fire' marker, NOT a frame), wrap back to type 1. Note: type 4 IS reached momentarily — enemy_type_dispatch runs FIRST and enqueues a bullet on type 4, then this routine wraps the type back to 1.
    LDA enemy_type,X
    CMP #&04
    BNE enemy_anim_done
    LDA #&01
    STA enemy_type,X
    RTS

.anim_toggle_8_9
    EOR #&01  \ Flame-firing enemy 2-state toggle. EOR #&01 flips between type &08 (about-to-fire pose; on the next dispatch call this triggers spawn_flame which itself bumps the slot to &09) and type &09 (post-fire idle).
    STA enemy_type,X
    RTS

.enemy_anim_done
    RTS  \ Shared 'no animation' RTS — branches here from enemy_anim_advance for enemy types that don't auto-advance their frame (force-fields, hazards already-advanced by dispatch, idle states).

.enemy_death_step
    INC enemy_type,X  \ Explosion-animation step for a dying enemy. INC enemy_type so it walks &14 → &15 → ... → &1B (= 8 frames using lev_enemy_ptr_*[20..27]); on reaching &1C clears the slot completely (enemy_type/_x/_y = 0). Triggered when an enemy's HP hits 0 (check_bullet_hits sets enemy_type = &14 to start the death anim).
    LDA enemy_type,X
    CMP #&1C
    BNE enemy_anim_done
    LDA #&00
    STA enemy_type,X
    STA enemy_x,X
    STA enemy_y,X
    RTS

.enemy_type_dispatch
    \ Enemy per-type IMMEDIATE action — called once per frame per active slot from update_enemy_slot, before frame-advance. Dispatch table by enemy_type[X]:
    \ type &04 → enqueue_enemy_bullet (small enemy fires a leftward 12×2-px red bullet; pool at enemy_bullet_x/_y, 7 slots)
    \ type &06 → spawn_enemy_missile (CODE2: launch a vertical 4×6-px yellow-red rocket that horizontally homes on the player; pool at enemy_missile_x/_y, 2 slots)
    \ type &07 → forcefield_render (this slot IS a force-field — re-noise the strip every frame)
    \ type &08 → spawn_flame (start the one-shot 32×8-px flame projectile; auto-mutates to type 9 on success)
    \ type &13 → enqueue_enemy_bullet (same as type 4 — second enemy variant that fires a bullet)
    \ else     → RTS (no per-frame action; the slot just gets drawn and frame-advanced).
    LDA enemy_type,X
    CMP #&04
    BNE L22BC
    JMP enqueue_enemy_bullet
.L22BC
    CMP #&13
    BNE L22CF
    JMP enqueue_enemy_bullet

.anim_set_type_10
    LDA #&10  \ Frame-advance for type-&0F enemies → set enemy_type = &10. Pairs with anim_set_type_F to form a 2-frame ping-pong (F↔10) for whichever enemy type this is (likely a 2-frame animated decor / persistent hazard with no death state).
    STA enemy_type,X
    RTS

.anim_set_type_F
    LDA #&0F  \ Frame-advance for type-&10 enemies → set enemy_type = &0F. The other half of the F↔10 ping-pong (see anim_set_type_10).
    STA enemy_type,X
    RTS
.L22CF
    CMP #&06
    BNE L22D6
    JMP spawn_enemy_missile
.L22D6
    CMP #&07
    BNE L22DD
    JMP forcefield_render
.L22DD
    CMP #&08
    BNE L22E4
    JMP spawn_flame
.L22E4
    RTS

.enqueue_enemy_bullet
    LDA zp_get_ready_erase  \ Enqueue an enemy bullet — called from enemy_type_dispatch for enemy types &04 and &13. Scans enemy_bullet_x[6..1] for a &FF (free) slot; on found, stores `enemy_x[firer] - 1` at enemy_bullet_x[slot] and `enemy_y[firer] - &10` at enemy_bullet_y[slot] (Y lifted by 16 px to fire from above the enemy). Plays sfx_fire. If the firer is already at enemy_x < &08 (almost off-screen left) the bullet is suppressed — there's not enough screen left for it to fly. Per-frame mover: update_enemy_bullets. The bullet sprite is a 12×2-px red dart (3-byte-col × 2-line block at lev_erase_brush+&100); the deactivation erase brush is at +&102.
    CMP #&02
    BEQ L22EC
    RTS
.L22EC
    LDX #&06
.L22EE
    LDA enemy_bullet_x,X
    CMP #&FF
    BEQ L22FC
    DEX
    BNE L22EE
    LDX data_16F5
    RTS
.L22FC
    STX data_16F6
    LDX data_16F5
    LDA enemy_x,X
    CMP #&08
    BCS L230D
    LDX data_16F5
    RTS
.L230D
    LDX data_16F6
    STA enemy_bullet_x,X
    DEC enemy_bullet_x,X
    LDX data_16F5
    LDA enemy_y,X
    LDX data_16F6
    SEC
    SBC #&10
    STA enemy_bullet_y,X
    JSR sfx_fire
    LDX data_16F5
    RTS

.forcefield_render
    LDA forcefield_active
    CMP #&01
    BNE L2334
    RTS
.L2334
    LDA #&01
    STA forcefield_active
    LDX data_16F5
    LDA enemy_y,X
    LDY enemy_flip,X
    BNE L234A
    SEC
    SBC #&20
    JMP forcefield_draw_or_erase
.L234A
    CLC
    ADC #&20

.forcefield_draw_or_erase
    STA forcefield_y
    LDA enemy_x,X
    STX data_16F8
    STA forcefield_x
    LDY forcefield_y
    TAX
    CPX #&02
    BCC forcefield_erase
    CPX #&25
    BCS forcefield_erase
    JSR calc_screen_addr
    JSR lfsr_random
    LDA rndval256
    STA sprite_src_lo
    LDA #&80
    STA sprite_src_hi
    LDX #&02
    LDY #&20
    JSR sprite_plot_xy
    LDA zp_player_x
    CMP forcefield_x
    BCS L23A1
    ADC #&04
    CMP forcefield_x
    BCC L23A1
    LDA zp_player_y
    SBC #&0C
    STA zp_test_x
    LDA forcefield_y
    CMP zp_test_x
    BCC L23A1
    SBC #&20
    CMP zp_test_x
    BCS L23A1
    JSR lose_a_life
.L23A1
    LDX data_16F8
    STX data_16F5
    RTS

.forcefield_erase
    JSR calc_screen_addr
    LDA #LO(lev_erase_brush + &80)
    STA sprite_src_lo
    LDA #HI(lev_erase_brush + &80)
    STA sprite_src_hi
    LDX #&02
    LDY #&20
    JSR sprite_plot_xy
    LDA #&00
    STA forcefield_active
    LDX data_16F5
    RTS

\ ----- data &23C5..&23C8 -----
.forcefield_x
    \ Force-field current X — last column it was drawn at; used by L210A to erase before forcefield_render redraws a fresh strip.
    EQUB &FF
.forcefield_y
    \ Force-field current Y — paired with forcefield_x.
    EQUB &FF
.forcefield_active
    \ Force-field active flag: 1 = a force-field was drawn last frame and needs erasing this frame, 0 = clean. Set by forcefield_draw_or_erase, cleared by L210A's early erase branch (and by forcefield_erase if the field went off-screen).
    EQUB &00

